@Francis

I'm not telling anybody how to do anything. I just speak from experience of being a child. You can't deny I was a child, right? Also, one does not have to have children to see how feeding them what amounts to industrial waste is a bad idea - just like I don't need to be a gun owner to understand what irresponsible handling of a gun looks like, say.

@Andrzej

An honest and non-threatening question...when you were poor in the 1980s, was it just you, or was it just about everyone?

I ask because I have heard a lot of people of the generation before me talking about poverty during the US Great Depression in the 30s, and to them it didn't seem so oppressive, because nearly everyone was in the same boat.

@Andrzej

In 1984, after graduating college and while living in Austria, I procured a visa to go traveling through a few eastern bloc countries.

I sold a pair of jeans in Poland and had enough money to live on for almost 2 weeks.

@Francis

I specifically wrote "we were all poor here in the 1980s". It wasn't oppressive, I guess, because the state actually provided the majority of people with enough to survive, including jobs and housing. Nobody thrived but few people starved. Yet compared to people in the West, we were all paupers. The prosperity of Austria, which I saw in 1988, was like something out of a fairytale. The houses of regular Austrians seemed like mansions, to me, and the displays of grocery shops (where we couldn't afford to shop) brought to mind the fantastical arrays of food described in the tales of 1001 nights.

We all experienced all new levels of poverty in the early 1990s, when the new democratic governemnt subjected the country to the shock therapy of introducing market economy practically overnight - in the end it turned out to be effective, but many people actually starved for a few years, before those who adjusted to the new system finally began to reap its benefits. Only years later did my parents confess to me how hard it was for them, and how they denied themselves many basics to, for example, be able to feed me right.

(Btw, isn't it amazing how three decades later Poland scores higher than the US in some quality-of-life indexes?)

@Bill in Yokohama

