Gap year and "studying abroad for the summer" are definitely associated with those who "suffer" from affluenza. However, I know kids who took a year off just clear their heads from all the clutter, while working two jobs (and getting tattoos) and saving their parents the expense. Then attended a junior college for core subjects, and finally got an in-state college. Those kids didn't use the term Gap Year, because of it's inference to the affluenziacs.

@Andrzej 

A "gap year" is between high school and college. It is specifically designed to give young people a break. It is a vacation year funded by their parents. Some may work, but I doubt that they'd consider it a "gap year."

